p6
aVThe first time I heard about Holocaust denial,
p7
aVI laughed.
p8
aVHolocaust denial?
p9
aVThe Holocaust which has the dubious distinction
p10
aVof being the best-documented genocide in the world?
p11
aVWho could believe it didn't happen?
p12
aa(lp13
VThink about it.
p14
aVFor deniers to be right,
p15
aVwho would have to be wrong?
p16
aVWell, first of all, the victims \u2014
p17
aVthe survivors who have told us their harrowing stories.
p18
aVWho else would have to be wrong?
p19
aVThe bystanders.
p20
aVThe people who lived in the myriads of towns and villages and cities
p21
aVon the Eastern front,
p22
aVwho watched their neighbors be rounded up \u2014
p23
aVmen, women, children, young, old \u2014
p24
aVand be marched to the outskirts of the town
p25
aVto be shot and left dead in ditches.
p26
aVOr the Poles,
p27
aVwho lived in towns and villages around the death camps,
p28
aVwho watched day after day
p29
aVas the trains went in filled with people
p30
aVand came out empty.
p31
aa(lp32
VBut above all, who would have to be wrong?
p33
aVThe perpetrators.
p34
aVThe people who say, "We did it.
p35
aVI did it."
p36
aVNow, maybe they add a caveat.
p37
aVThey say, "I didn't have a choice; I was forced to do it."
