aa(lp181
VNow, lots of my academic colleagues counseled me \u2014
p182
aV"Eh, Deborah, just ignore it."
p183
aVWhen I explained you can't just ignore a libel suit,
p184
aVthey said, "Who's going to believe him anyway?"
p185
aVBut here was the problem:
p186
aVBritish law put the onus, put the burden of proof on me
p187
aVto prove the truth of what I said,
p188
aVin contrast to as it would have been in the United States
p189
aVand in many other countries:
p190
aVon him to prove the falsehood.
p191
aa(lp192
VWhat did that mean?
p193
aVThat meant if I didn't fight,
p194
aVhe would win by default.
p195
aVAnd if he won by default,
p196
aVhe could then legitimately say,
p197
aV"My David Irving version of the Holocaust is a legitimate version.
p198
aVDeborah Lipstadt was found to have libeled me
p199
aVwhen she called me a Holocaust denier.
p200
aVIpso facto, I, David Irving, am not a Holocaust denier."
