aa(lp283
VThird of all:
p284
aVextremism.
p285
aVYou may not see Ku Klux Klan robes,
p286
aVyou may not see burning crosses,
p287
aVyou may not even hear outright white supremacist language.
p288
aVIt may go by names: "alt-right," "National Front" \u2014 pick your names.
p289
aVBut underneath, it's that same extremism that I found in Holocaust denial
p290
aVparading as rational discourse.
p291
aa(lp292
VWe live in an age where truth is on the defensive.
p293
aVI'm reminded of a New Yorker cartoon.
p294
aVA quiz show recently appeared in "The New Yorker"
p295
aVwhere the host of the quiz show is saying to one of the contestants,
p296
aV"Yes, ma'am, you had the right answer.
p297
aVBut your opponent yelled more loudly than you did,
p298
aVso he gets the point."
p299
aa(lp300
VWhat can we do?
p301
aVFirst of all,
p302
aVwe cannot be beguiled by rational appearances.
p303
aVWe've got to look underneath,
p304
aVand we will find there the extremism.
p305
aVSecond of all,
p306
aVwe must understand that truth is not relative.
p307
aVNumber three,
p308
aVwe must go on the offensive,
p309
aVnot the defensive.
p310
aVWhen someone makes an outrageous claim,
p311
aVeven though they may hold one of the highest offices in the land,
p312
aVif not the world \u2014
p313
aVwe must say to them,
p314
aV"Where's the proof?
p315
aVWhere's the evidence?"
p316
aVWe must hold their feet to the fire.
p317
aVWe must not treat it as if their lies are the same as the facts.
p318
aa(lp319
VAnd as I said earlier, truth is not relative.
p320
aVMany of us have grown up in the world of the academy
p321
aVand enlightened liberal thought,
p322
aVwhere we're taught everything is open to debate.
p323
aVBut that's not the case.
